import json, os, sys

def load_comm(layer, book):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    if os.path.exists(path):
        with open(path) as f:
            return json.load(f)
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(path), exist_ok=True)
    with open(path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(data, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)
    print(f'wrote {path}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

JUDGES = {
    "17": {
        "1": "<p>Micah's introduction as a man of the hill country of Ephraim establishes the story's social geography: away from the tribal centre, in the marginal uplands where covenant life is weakest. The name Micah (Hebrew mîkāyāh, 'who is like YHWH?') is richly ironic — the man whose name asks the incomparability question will spend the chapter fashioning a competing deity. Christ as the eternal Son is the answer to Micah's name-question: no one is like YHWH, and the Son is the exact imprint of his nature (Heb 1:3), not an image cast by human hands.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Micah confesses the theft of 1,100 pieces of silver from his own mother; she had uttered a curse over the loss, and Micah fears it. The confession extracts a blessing but not genuine repentance — the silver will immediately fund the very idolatry it should have prevented. The blessing-curse dynamic here is one of self-managed religion: curses deflected by ritual, blessings purchased by confession. The NT contrast is the freely given blessing of God in Christ through genuine repentance (Acts 3:19), where forgiveness is not a transaction but an act of grace.</p>",
        "3": "<p>Micah's mother declares the silver 'consecrated to YHWH' for the purpose of making a carved image and a metal idol. The theological contradiction is total: silver given to YHWH is immediately diverted to manufacture what YHWH explicitly forbids (Ex 20:4–6). This is a paradigm of syncretism — using covenant language ('consecrated to YHWH') to legitimise uncovenant practice. Christ is the image of the invisible God (Col 1:15) who makes all carved representations unnecessary; the Word made flesh is the only authorised self-presentation of YHWH to human eyes.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Two hundred pieces are given to the silversmith; the remainder presumably retained by the mother. The idol is installed in Micah's house — a domestic shrine in the private sector. In the ancient world, household gods were common; this Israelite version is doubly corrupt because it wraps covenant vocabulary around Canaanite practice. The incarnation replaced all household-religion substitutes: Christ dwelling in the believer (John 14:23; Eph 3:17) is the true divine presence in the house, requiring no cast image.</p>",
        "7": "<p>A Levite from Bethlehem-Judah arrives as a sojourner in the hill country of Ephraim. Levites were the tribe of priests, without territorial allotment, dependent on the covenant community's hospitality. This one's displacement from Bethlehem (ironically, 'house of bread' — where David will be born and where Christ will be born) to wander shows the disintegration of the Levitical system. The wandering Levite is a dark parody of the shepherding priest; Christ is the Good Shepherd who does not wander but seeks the lost (Luke 15:4–7).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The Levite leaves Bethlehem-Judah 'to sojourn wherever he might find a place.' The phrase captures ministerial opportunism: vocation is replaced by circumstance. He has no particular assignment, no congregation, no covenantal calling — only availability for whoever will hire. This aimlessness contrasts with Christ's decisive mission ('I came from God and am going to God,' John 13:3; 'The Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost,' Luke 19:10). The true Priest is sent; he does not wander.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The Levite's self-introduction — 'I am a Levite of Bethlehem-Judah, and I am going to sojourn wherever I find a place' — is the ministerial résumé of the era of no-king chaos. His Levitical identity is his credential, but he has no post and no sending community. The contrast with the appointed priesthood of Christ (Heb 5:4–5, 'not self-appointed but called by God') is sharp: Christ did not seize the priesthood opportunistically but was formally appointed 'a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek.'</p>",
        "10": "<p>Micah's offer — 'stay with me, and be to me a father and priest, and I will give you ten pieces of silver a year, and a suit of clothes and your living' — reduces the priestly office to a household staff position. The Levite is offered wages, clothing, and board: the priest as domestic employee. This is the commercialisation of the sacred. The NT critiques the same dynamic in the hired hand who abandons the flock (John 10:12–13); Christ, the unpaid Good Shepherd, lays down his life rather than receiving a salary.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The Levite agrees and becomes 'like one of his sons' — domestic, familial, fully integrated into Micah's private religious economy. The Levite's agreement is not singled out as exceptional wickedness; it is simply what made sense in a world without covenant accountability. The church's NT pattern is elders whose call comes from the congregation and ultimately from Christ (Acts 20:28; 1 Pet 5:1–4), not from private patrons who set the terms of ministry.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Micah 'installed the Levite, and the young man became his priest.' The verb 'installed' (Hebrew millē' yād, literally 'filled the hand') is the standard ordination idiom — used properly in Leviticus for Aaron's consecration. Micah applies it in a domestic context to a priest he hired. Ordination by money rather than divine call is the theological error here. Christ's Melchizedekan priesthood (Heb 7:16) is 'not based on a legal requirement concerning bodily descent but on the power of an indestructible life' — appointment from an altogether different source.</p>"
    },
    "18": {
        "2": "<p>The five Danite spies are described as 'men of valor' — military language applied to a reconnaissance mission for territory the tribe had failed to secure by faith. They arrive at Micah's house and recognise the Levite's voice. The chance encounter will redefine Israelite religion in the north for generations. The pattern — military strength seeking religious endorsement — recurs throughout Israel's history and reaches its nadir in Jeroboam's bull-calf cult. Christ refused to align his mission with military power (John 6:15; Matt 4:8–10), the opposite of this Danite strategy.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The spies' question — 'Who brought you here? What do you do here? What is your purpose here?' — inadvertently interrogates the nature of illegitimate ministry. Three questions that expose the hired Levite's position: no proper sender, no covenantal function, no divine purpose. In John 1:19–23, the priests and Levites ask similar questions of John the Baptist, who answers from divine calling. The contrast is instructive: a Levite who cannot answer 'who sent you' versus the Baptist who points to the one who comes after him.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The Levite explains his situation: 'Micah has done such and such for me, and he hired me, and I have become his priest.' The summary of his entire ministry in terms of a commercial transaction is damning. The NT apostles defined their call in terms of divine commissioning and sacrifice (2 Cor 5:20; Acts 20:24), not employment terms. Christ sent the Twelve with nothing — no salary, no guarantee of hospitality — to model a ministry of giving rather than being hired (Matt 10:8–10).</p>",
        "5": "<p>The spies ask the Levite to 'inquire of God' about their mission. That they turn to a private chaplain for a military oracle reveals the degradation of prophecy: divination is now available for hire. The oracle they receive (v6) is generic enough to mean anything. True prophecy in Israel spoke unwanted truth to power (1 Kgs 22:13–14; Jer 28); this oracle serves the client. Christ himself refused to perform signs on demand (Matt 12:38–39) and predicted false prophets who tell people what they want to hear (Matt 7:15).</p>",
        "6": "<p>The Levite's oracle — 'Go in peace; the journey on which you go is before YHWH' — is maximally vague and certainly positive. It is exactly what the clients wanted to hear. The phenomenon of an oracle that always affirms the questioner's desired course of action is a marker of false prophecy throughout the OT (Jer 6:14, 'peace, peace, when there is no peace'). The NT warns against teachers who 'tickle ears' (2 Tim 4:3–4); Christ's teaching regularly denied his audience comfortable answers (Luke 14:25–33).</p>",
        "7": "<p>Laish is described as a city whose people 'lived in security, after the manner of the Sidonians, quiet and unsuspecting, with no one in the land possessing authority to put them to shame in anything.' Their vulnerability is their peaceful isolation — no military alliance, no nearby protector. The Danites will exploit this security to commit massacre. The ease of the conquest underlines its moral problem: there is no enemy here, only a peaceful city. Christ's mission was to the lost and the vulnerable, not to dispossess the peaceful (Luke 4:18–19).</p>",
        "8": "<p>The scouts return to Zorah and Eshtaol — the territory they cannot take from its stronger inhabitants — and report to their kinsmen. Their report will trigger the migration of the whole tribe. The pattern of sending scouts, receiving favourable report, and mobilising for conquest echoes the Mosaic spy narrative (Num 13–14), but there the conquest of inhabited Canaanite land was covenantally commanded; here it is tribal opportunism against peaceful Laish. The christological contrast is Abraham who 'looked for the city that has foundations, whose architect and builder is God' (Heb 11:10), not a city seized by strength.</p>",
        "9": "<p>'Arise, let us go up against them, for we have seen the land, and behold, it is very good.' The echo of the Promised Land spy language ('the land is very good') applied to an unapproved conquest of peaceful Laish shows how covenant narrative can be hijacked for self-interest. The rhetoric of divine gift becomes the rhetoric of military ambition. Christ's kingdom comes not by territorial conquest but by the weakness of the cross (1 Cor 1:18–25); the 'very good land' of the NT is the coming new creation, not seized by arms.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The promise 'God has given it into your hand — a place where there is no lack of anything' echoes covenant blessing language (Deut 28) transposed onto an unsanctioned raid. The oracle of the hired Levite (v6) is now applied retroactively to justify conquest of Laish. This is the pattern of reading divine approval backward from success: if it worked, God must have willed it. Christ warned against this reasoning (Luke 13:1–5), and the prophets repeatedly challenged the 'God is on our side' assumption when Israel violated covenant ethics.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Six hundred armed Danites set out from Zorah and Eshtaol. The number 600 recurs in Judges as a militarily significant force (Judg 3:31; 20:47); it is also the number of men who escape to the rock of Rimmon in the later civil war (Judg 20:47). The military mobilisation of an entire tribe for an unapproved migration-by-conquest is the apex of the 'no king' chaos: armies move without divine mandate or prophetic sanction. The NT church advances not by armed force but by proclamation (2 Cor 10:4–5).</p>",
        "12": "<p>The camp at Kiriath-jearim — 'behind Judah,' west of Jerusalem — becomes 'Mahaneh-dan' (Camp of Dan). The naming is significant: this is how the tribe marks its departure from its allotted territory. Kiriath-jearim will later become famous as the resting place of the ark of the covenant (1 Sam 7:2; 2 Sam 6:2), the true divine presence, before David brings it to Jerusalem. The Danites camping here in their march toward idolatry is a dark irony — passing the site of YHWH's ark on their way to install a stolen idol.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The Danites proceed to the hill country of Ephraim and come to Micah's house — the same route the five spies had taken. The larger force retraces the scouts' path, normalising the original reconnaissance as the prelude to planned theft. In the ancient world, household gods protected a home; to remove them was to strip it of divine protection. The Danites are about to perform exactly this violation. Christ's teaching on the strong man's house (Luke 11:21–22) describes a binding and plundering that is legitimate (against Satan); the Danite raid is the illegitimate parody.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The Danites enter Micah's house and greet the Levite, while the 600 armed men stand at the gate. The juxtaposition — friendly greeting inside, armed force outside — captures the mechanics of religious coercion. The hired Levite is about to receive a better offer. The passage illustrates how external force shapes internal 'choice': the Levite will agree freely, but the agreement is made in the shadow of 600 swords. True religious vocation requires freedom; Christ's call is to 'follow me' voluntarily (Matt 4:19; 16:24), never under armed compulsion.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The six hundred armed Danites stand at the gate while the five spies enter to take the cult objects. The military escort frames what is technically a theft as something between seizure and an offer the Levite cannot refuse. The armed presence transforms the scene from robbery into something resembling an official requisition. The misuse of organised force to accomplish religious ends is a recurring failure in Israelite history; Christ rejected the option of twelve legions of angels (Matt 26:53) to accomplish his redemptive purpose.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The five men take the carved image, the ephod, the household gods, and the metal image while the priest and the armed men stand at the gate. The cult objects are carried off piece by piece: the entire apparatus of Micah's private religion is confiscated. In the ancient world, capturing an enemy's gods was the supreme trophy of conquest, signifying that the victor's deity had overpowered the defeated deity. The Danites apply this theology domestically: taking Micah's gods to install in their own shrine. The God of Israel cannot be captured or transported; Christ is present wherever two or three gather in his name (Matt 18:20).</p>",
        "18": "<p>When the Levite protests ('What are you doing?'), the five men ask in return: 'What do you say? Keep quiet; put your hand on your mouth and come with us and be to us a father and priest.' The demand for the Levite's silence ('put your hand on your mouth') is the gesture of overwhelming awe before the divine in Job 40:4 and Micah 7:16 — here applied as an order to suppress objection to theft. Coercive silence imposed on a priest inverts prophetic calling. Christ gave his ministers freedom and obligation to speak (Acts 4:18–20; Rev 2–3).</p>",
        "20": "<p>The Levite's heart was glad, and he took the ephod, household gods, and image and went among the people. His gladness signals the transition from protest to complicity: a better position has been offered, and he accepts it without moral reservation. The heart's gladness at occupational advancement over against covenantal fidelity is a precise portrait of mercenary ministry. The NT test of a true minister is whether he 'runs' for gain or 'feeds the flock' (1 Pet 5:2–3; 1 Tim 6:9–10); the Levite's glad compliance indicts the heart that measures ministry by career opportunity.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The Danites resume their journey, putting their wives, children, and livestock ahead and the armed men behind — a military march formation protecting the most vulnerable. The care for the weak in the march contrasts with the moral carelessness of their mission. The detail humanises the Danites even as the narrative condemns their apostasy: they are a whole community, not simply warriors, displacing toward an unlawful shrine. The mixed picture resists caricature and invites the reader to see the full community consequences of leadership failure.</p>",
        "22": "<p>When they had gone some distance from Micah's house, the men who were in the houses near Micah were called out and overtook the Danites. The pursuit scene has the quality of a parable: Micah, having lost his gods and his priest, discovers that private religion offers no community protection. His neighbours rally to his cause (the 'houses near Micah'), but they are a village militia against 600 armed men. The theft of the gods he thought would prosper him (17:13) has left him defenceless — the opposite of what he expected. Idolatry cannot deliver what it promises (Is 46:7).</p>",
        "23": "<p>The Danites ask Micah: 'What is the matter with you that you called out the men?' The question performs studied innocence — the aggressors asking the victim to account for his complaint. Micah's response ('you have taken my gods that I made, and the priest') is the clearest statement of the problem: the gods are things he made, and the priest is a hire. Both are human constructs, not covenantal gifts. His gods can be stolen because they are manufactured objects. The living God cannot be taken captive (1 Kgs 8:27); when Babylon 'captured' YHWH's temple, YHWH himself had already departed (Ezek 10–11).</p>",
        "24": "<p>'You have taken my gods that I made and the priest, and you have gone away, and what do I have left? How then do you ask me, What is the matter with you?' Micah's lament is genuinely pathetic — a man stripped of the religion he built with his own hands. His gods are gone and his priest is gone, and he has nothing left. The emptiness of idolatry is exposed: when the manufactured deity can be carried off, the worshipper is left with nothing. Christ cannot be taken away: 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20); 'I will never leave you nor forsake you' (Heb 13:5).</p>",
        "25": "<p>The Danites' warning — 'do not let your voice be heard among us, or angry fellows will attack you, and you will lose your life' — ends the pursuit. Micah turns back, unwilling to risk death for his manufactured religion. The willingness to die for something is the measure of ultimate value; Micah's gods are not worth dying for. Christ 'laid down his life for us' (1 John 3:16); the apostles counted their lives not worth keeping (Acts 20:24; Rev 12:11). True faith produces martyrs; idolatry produces pragmatic survivors.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Micah goes home, and the Danites go on their way. The episode concludes with both parties returning to their trajectories — Micah to his stripped house, the Danites to their appointed conquest. The separation is permanent: Micah's religious project has been permanently disrupted, the Danites have acquired their shrine-in-transit. The unresolved tragedy of Micah's loss is not softened by the narrative. The NT's resolution of private religious failure is not 'get a better shrine' but repentance and incorporation into the body of Christ (1 Cor 12:12–13).</p>",
        "27": "<p>The Danites take what Micah had made and the priest, and come to Laish — to a people who are quiet and unsuspecting. They strike them with the edge of the sword and burn the city. The combination of stolen cult objects and massacre of peaceful civilians is the nadir of Danite behaviour. The god who could not protect Micah's house is now installed over a city built on blood. Christ's kingdom is founded on the shedding of his own blood, not the blood of others (Eph 2:13); the Danite pattern inverts the christological pattern at every point.</p>",
        "28": "<p>'There was no deliverer because it was far from Sidon and they had no dealings with anyone.' Laish's peaceful isolation, which made it attractive as a target, also made it defenceless. The narrative mourns the absence of a deliverer. The word 'deliverer' (môšîa') is the vocabulary of Israel's judges and ultimately of the messianic deliverer (Is 45:21; 49:26). The absence of a deliverer for Laish points forward to the whole Judges narrative's need for the final Deliverer — the one who comes not to massacre the peaceful but to rescue the captive (Luke 4:18).</p>",
        "29": "<p>The Danites rebuild and name the city Dan after their ancestor, son of Israel. The renaming marks the permanent Danite stamp on the northern geography; 'from Dan to Beersheba' becomes the standard formula for all Israel (Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 3:20). But Dan's founding is built on apostasy, theft, and massacre. The city will later become one of Jeroboam's bull-calf sites (1 Kgs 12:29–30) — the idolatrous theology of Judges 17–18 carried forward into the divided monarchy. Revelation 7's absence of Dan from the sealed 144,000 may reflect this long-established association with apostasy.</p>"
    },
    "19": {
        "3": "<p>The Levite goes after his concubine, 'to speak tenderly to her' — the Hebrew literally 'to speak to her heart,' the language of wooing and reconciliation (Gen 34:3; Hos 2:14). He brings his servant and a couple of donkeys: a small retinue for a personal mission. The gesture of reconciliation is not without ambiguity — the same Levite will later hand her to the mob — but the tender intention establishes the depth of the subsequent betrayal. Christ speaks to the heart of his bride (Hos 2:14–15) and does not abandon her; the Levite's initial tenderness makes his later failure more damning by contrast.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The father-in-law receives him joyfully; they eat and drink, and he stays three days. The hospitality is excessive and warm — a sharp contrast to the inhospitality of Gibeah that will follow. The number three days echoes the typical OT journey pattern (Ex 3:18; 2 Kgs 20:5) and narratively delays the departure toward tragedy. The father's joy at his son-in-law's return is genuine, making the Levite's passivity during his concubine's assault all the more conspicuous: here a man is glad to see him; there a crowd will want to assault him.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The father-in-law urges him to eat and strengthen himself before going. The repeated delay motif (vv5–8) has been variously interpreted: as ANE hospitality custom, as the narrator slowing the pace before catastrophe, or as the Levite's own comfort-seeking that will delay his departure too long. The food and comfort of the father-in-law's house will end; the night in Gibeah will bring horror. The gospel reversal is that Christ's followers are urged to be nourished for a journey that leads through suffering, not away from it (John 6:51–58).</p>",
        "6": "<p>He lingers again; they eat and drink together. The father-in-law's second invitation to stay is accepted. The pattern of eating, fellowship, and delay creates a rhythm of domestic warmth that the narrative will shatter. The theological use of communal eating in the Bible — from the covenant meals of Exodus to the Last Supper to the marriage supper of the Lamb — contrasts with the Gibeah horror: table fellowship violated, hospitality weaponised. Christ restores the meal to its redemptive purpose (1 Cor 11:26).</p>",
        "7": "<p>The Levite rises to go, but his father-in-law presses him and he stays again. The narrator gives no dialogue, only repeated action: urged, stays; urged, stays. The delay that was initially hospitable becomes comically extended, and the reader can feel the momentum of the narrative building despite (because of) the domestic stasis. The irony is structural: this man who will make a catastrophic last-minute departure is now unable to leave at all. The NT's eschatological call is to readiness and watchfulness (Matt 25:1–13) rather than the comfortable delay that makes the final departure dangerous.</p>",
        "8": "<p>On the fifth day he rises early; the father-in-law urges him to wait until afternoon, and they eat together. The extended hospitality has become a kind of paralysis. They finally set out late in the day, arriving near Jebus as the sun goes down. The timing — departing too late to reach safe shelter in a friendly city — is the narrative pivot that sends him to Gibeah. A decision shaped by comfort and delay produces catastrophe. The wisdom literature's warnings about sluggardness and untimeliness find their narrative embodiment here.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The final farewell: the father-in-law urges him to stay one more night and return fresh in the morning. The Levite refuses and departs with his concubine and servant at late afternoon. The refusal is the one act of decisiveness in the entire delay sequence — and it is the wrong decision, taken too late for safety. The narrative does not blame the Levite for leaving; it exposes the entire sequence of delays as the context that made a late departure inevitable. Wisdom required leaving earlier; comfort made that impossible.</p>",
        "10": "<p>They come opposite Jebus (Jerusalem), 'with the day far spent.' The servant suggests stopping at the city of the Jebusites; the Levite refuses — 'we will not turn aside into the city of foreigners who do not belong to the people of Israel.' The choice of Gibeah over Jebus is the final fatal decision: he trusts kinship over hospitality, Israelite over foreigner. Ironically, the Jebusite city would have been safer. Jerusalem will become the city of David and ultimately the city of God — the place of true hospitality — only after conquest and covenant. The Levite bypasses the future city of peace for a Benjaminite city that will prove to be worse than Sodom.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The servant's suggestion to stop at Jebus is presented as prudent — 'let us turn aside to this city of the Jebusites and spend the night in it.' The Levite overrules him. The servant's voice here is functionally prophetic: a lower-status figure offering better counsel that is ignored. The pattern (subordinate counsel rejected by higher authority with catastrophic results) recurs throughout the Historical Books. Christ reversed the status hierarchy of counsel: 'the least among you all is the one who is greatest' (Luke 9:48); wisdom comes from unexpected sources.</p>",
        "12": "<p>'We will not turn aside into the city of foreigners, who do not belong to the people of Israel, but we will pass on to Gibeah.' The Levite's reasoning is ethnic — the foreigner's city is not safe for an Israelite. The tragic irony is complete: the Israelite city will prove far more dangerous than the foreign one. The logic of 'our people are safer' is exposed as false, and worse — it is false precisely because of covenant failure. Israel's special status should mean greater covenant faithfulness, not tribal violence; the failure of Gibeah is the failure of election without sanctification.</p>",
        "13": "<p>They will spend the night at Gibeah or Ramah, 'which belongs to Benjamin.' The Levite is choosing shelter based on tribal affiliation: a fellow Israelite tribe should be hospitable. The expectation of tribal solidarity — kinship as guarantee of safety — will be catastrophically violated. The NT's community of hospitality transcends tribal and ethnic boundaries (Heb 13:2; Gal 3:28); the early church's hospitality to strangers and pilgrims represented a redefinition of who counts as 'family.' The Levite's tribal calculus would have excluded the Good Samaritan from helping the wounded traveller (Luke 10:30–37).</p>",
        "15": "<p>They enter Gibeah and sit in the town square, but no one takes them in for the night. The open square where travellers waited for an offer of hospitality is the test of a city's covenant faithfulness; in Gen 19:1–2, Lot immediately meets Sodom's angels in the gateway. At Gibeah, no one comes. The city of Benjamin — an Israelite tribe, possessors of the covenant — fails the hospitality test that Abraham passed (Gen 18:1–8) and that Lot, a resident alien, passed in Sodom. Inhospitality is a covenant category failure, which is why Ezekiel lists it among Sodom's sins (Ezek 16:49).</p>",
        "16": "<p>An old man returning from his field in the evening sees the traveller in the street. The detail 'returning from his field in the evening' establishes him as a working farmer who has not been watching for travellers — yet when he sees them, he acts. He is also an Ephraimite sojourning in Benjamin: a northerner living among Benjaminites, which explains why he practices the hospitality that the Benjaminites themselves have withheld. The outsider extending hospitality to those refused by the insider community is a recurring gospel pattern (Luke 10:33–35; the Samaritan vs. the priest and Levite).</p>",
        "17": "<p>The old man asks: 'Where are you going and where do you come from?' The question mirrors the travel narrative's structure — origin and destination — but more deeply it echoes the divine question to exiles and wanderers throughout scripture (Gen 3:9; 16:8; Jonah 1:8). The Levite is passing through a world that should be covenant community but has become a wilderness. The old man's question opens the space for hospitality that the city itself has closed. Christ's encounters with travellers (Luke 24:13–17) begin with the same relational inquiry: 'What are you discussing as you walk?'</p>",
        "18": "<p>The Levite's answer — 'We are passing from Bethlehem-Judah to the remote parts of the hill country of Ephraim, from where I come. I went to Bethlehem-Judah, and I am going to the house of YHWH, but no one has taken me into his house' — is the summary of his failure. He claims to be 'going to the house of YHWH' (presumably Shiloh, where the tabernacle is) yet no one has offered hospitality in a city of the covenant people. The phrase 'no one has taken me into his house' is the covenant indictment of Gibeah: a man going to YHWH's house has been excluded from every human house along the way. Christ came to his own, and his own did not receive him (John 1:11).</p>",
        "19": "<p>The Levite assures the old man that they have sufficient provisions — straw and feed for the donkeys, bread and wine for themselves — and that they need only shelter. The self-sufficiency statement is part of ANE guest protocol: the traveller demonstrates he will not be a burden. The detail of the provision list (straw, bread, wine, oil, cloth) mirrors the list of tabernacle/temple offerings, subtly associating the traveller's dignity with sacred hospitality. Christ's table hospitality (Mark 6:41; John 2:1–11) provides from abundance, not from the guest's own resources.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The old man says: 'Peace be to you; I will care for all your needs; only, do not spend the night in the square.' His welcome is comprehensive — 'all your needs' — and his warning urgent: the square is not safe for travellers at Gibeah. The urgency of the warning signals the old man's local knowledge of the danger. He knows what the city is. Peace (shalom) is offered inside his house while violence waits outside. The house of the old Ephraimite becomes a temporary sanctuary in a city of predators. Christ is the one who offers shalom at the threshold (John 20:19, 21, 26) when the world outside is hostile.</p>",
        "21": "<p>He brings them in and feeds their donkeys, then they wash their feet and eat and drink. The full hospitality sequence — shelter, animal care, foot-washing, meal — is the complete ANE hospitality rite. Foot-washing in particular is an act of welcome-honour (Gen 18:4; Luke 7:44; John 13:1–5). In a chapter that will pivot to horrific violation of the body, the foot-washing stands as a tender prelude. Christ took the foot-washing gesture and gave it permanent theological meaning: the host who becomes servant, the Lord who washes (John 13:13–15). Here the old man enacts it; the men of Gibeah will violate the body it represents.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The old man goes out to the men of Gibeah and says: 'No, my brothers, do not act so wickedly; since this man has come into my house, do not do this vile thing.' His appeal to brotherhood ('my brothers') and covenant ethics ('do not act so wickedly,' 'vile thing') deploys the language of Israelite covenant community against men who have abandoned it. The word 'vile' (Hebrew nĕbālāh) is the language of covenant outrage — the same word used for Shechem's rape of Dinah (Gen 34:7) and Tamar's rape by Amnon (2 Sam 13:12). The old man names the moral category correctly; the crowd refuses it. Jesus named the vile thing at his trial (Mark 14:64) and was condemned for it.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The old man offers his virgin daughter and the Levite's concubine: 'Let me bring them out. Violate them and do with them what seems good to you, but against this man do not do this outrageous thing.' The offer is morally catastrophic: female bodies used as a negotiating currency to protect male honour. The parallel with Lot's offer of his daughters (Gen 19:8) is explicit and intentional; the Gibeah narrative is the Sodom narrative transposed onto Israel. The contrast with Christ's self-offering is total: he placed himself between the violent world and the vulnerable (John 15:13; Gal 2:20), not offering others in his place.</p>",
        "26": "<p>At dawn, the woman falls at the door of the old man's house, her hands on the threshold. The threshold — the place of boundary between safety and danger, inside and outside — is where she collapses. She came back to the last place of refuge and could not enter. The image of the abused woman lying at the threshold of hospitality, unable to cross back in, is one of scripture's most haunting. The gospel image is its inversion: Christ as the door (John 10:9), through whom the sheep enter safely — a threshold that opens outward into grace rather than closing in abandonment.</p>",
        "27": "<p>Her master rises in the morning, opens the doors, and goes out to continue his journey — and she is there, fallen at the door. The verb 'her master' (ba'alāh) frames the Levite's relationship to the concubine in terms of ownership, not covenant love. His immediate purpose on rising is to continue the journey; the discovery of his concubine's collapsed body is incidental to that plan. The NT pattern is the shepherd who leaves the ninety-nine to find the one (Luke 15:4); the Levite's pattern is the master who steps over the fallen one to resume travel. Christ does not step over the wounded; he binds and carries (Luke 10:34; Matt 11:28–30).</p>"
    }
}

